<span id="page_77">p. 77</span>

#### III. Scoticè

<div style="font-size: 90%">

The *Chün Tzŭ Yang Yang;* narrative. The husband's satisfaction, and the
wife's joy, on his return.

</div>

<div style="margin-left: 20%; margin-right: 20%; font-size: 110%;">

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_1">1</span></span>The gudeman’s come
hame, an’ his face weers a bloom,  
  His organ o’ reeds he hads in his left han’;  
An’ his richt han’ ca’s me to come till his room:—  
  It’s siccan a joy; it’s mair nor I can stan’.

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_2">2</span></span>The gudeman’s come
hame, an’ he’s pleesed I’ll engage,  
  His gran’ fether screen he hads in his left han’;  
An’ his richt han’ ca’s me to come till the stage:—  
  It’s siccan a joy; it’s mair nor I can stan’.

</div>

